{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "In particular, the Adam-variants of Optimistic Gradient Descent Ascent (OGDA), the ExtraGradient approach, and these methods are discussed.",
    "Their performance, robustness, and stability are assessed and compared using the cutting-edge GAN designs U-Net GAN and Style-GAN 2.",
    "The empirical evidence on U-Net GAN strongly suggest that the Adam-variants of OGDA and ExtraGradient, as compared to the most popular optimization schemes in contemporary GAN training, regular SGDA and Adam, are more resilient to different choices of hyperparameter settings and less likely to collapse mid-training.",
    "However, employing the Adam-variants of OGDA and ExtraGradient had little effect on the final findings for a well-tuned, well-functioning Adam setup like StyleGAN 2.",
    "This suggests that while SGDA and Adam are still needed for reaching state-of-the-art performance, these algorithms are more dependable and user-friendly.Byun et al. [64] suggested a hybrid GAN technique to address the issue of data imbalance and improve the effectiveness of recommendation systems."
  ],
